      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Mideast Tragedy</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Dr Heskel M Haddad, World Organization for Jews From Arab Countries, says Ariel Sharon's visit to Temple Mount was provocative, but Palestinians used it as excuse for violent and possibly planned outbreak</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Rosh Hashana was ruined for me this year when I read the story of the 12-year-old boy who was killed in the Gaza riots (news article, Oct. 2).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Rosh Hashana was ruined for me this year when I read the story of the 12-year-old boy who was killed in the Gaza riots (news article, Oct. 2).</p>
        <p>However, this tragedy should open the eyes of the political and religious leaders who insist on inciting violence. There is no question that the visit of the Likud leader, Ariel Sharon, to the Temple Mount was provocative, but it was simply an excuse for the violent and possibly planned outbreak.</p>
        <p>Israel must defend itself or perish. Palestinians know that Israel will defend itself against threats and that this defense will lead to killing. Until the Arabs respect recent commitments to peace and cease stone-throwing, sniping and roadside bombing, the cycle of violence will continue.</p>
        <p>HESKEL M. HADDAD, M.D.  New York, Oct. 2, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is president of the World Organization for Jews From Arab Countries.</p>
      </block>
